Kalam

Book of Linmus

<This journal has many entries, much destroyed or of little interest. Half of the journal is blank, but some pages near the center can be read>


...and so we went out of the cave. It was too dark to see much, for it was still night. But before us the desert was like a new-found hope. Though it was flat and unforgiving we crossed it, fighting large blue dragons and elementals of many kinds. Razeem, our guide, was slain by one of these beasts...


...we came to an ancient city, half buried under the shifting sands. A huge temple stood at the far edge of a chasm that surrounded the old city. We tried to enter, but the doors were blocked by fallen rubble. After two days we cleared the rubble, but our numbers were growing slim from the constant attacks of evil undead...


...now we are down to just myself, Delph Twotoes, Haj the mage and my faithful guard Halbert. I fear we shall never leave this place. The undead are too strong and too many to retreat...

...and this shall be my last entry. We have found a crypt. But it is guarded by the foulest of evil. We entered, but the door slammed shut behind us. I cower in a corner over my guards body as I write these last lines. I only hope someone will find this journal and know of our fate. My last thoughts go out to my fiance, waiting patiently in Benzor for my return.  <there is a small scribble of a name> -Artemus Linmus-
Tome of Linmus

Book of Favors

Details of various potions, most are unintelligable and for commonplace hexes and aids.


...after heating cauldron to the boiling point, throw in a handful of sassafrass. Mix four parts of dragons blood with a lock of hair from your desired love interest. When he or she comes calling, make sure they breath deeply the aroma of the resulting brew. It is suggested that two days time elapse for full potency.
Book Of Favors

<paper sheet filled with diagrams of green dragons, with some notes>


Be it known! And the lands erupted with spouts of water and steam. The green dragons came forth in their hatred of all things good and pure. They befoul and scourge!

I, Hafa, shall demean them in my glory and prudence. Their eggs will be sundered and they shall know that doom awaits them!
The Land of Mist

<This scroll starts out with planning notes for going to the desert. It has a brief description at the bottom>


...and the region is harsh indeed. Those that rest, or make camp are slowly swallowed in the mud and salt flats. There is a broad stretch of this sterile and heat-heavy flat. Blue dragons make their nests here, all female and brooding over the eggs they leave in the sands. Somewhere to the north, we are told, is a lord of these desert blues. But as of this writing the lair of this beast has not been located. The dervishers continue to keep us from proper rest, and we must return to Hebdezi to sleep and reequip each time we explore.

...not much can survive the intense heat of the flats, there are no cacti, no water at all, no rocks puncture the surface but for those that surround the wastes. The remains of lost wayfarers sometimes float to the surface, but little else can be found.

...the origins of these flats is shrouded, but is somehow tied to the destruction of Abiz. On the far northern reaches lies a vast chasm, the flats become broken and charred by some cataclysm far in the past. Small bits of strange metal can be found there, tests on these pieces have unearthed no clues as to their origin. They are very sharp and we are looking into having them used in magic.
The Sterile Wastes

A scroll detailing some odd dish


...mix four parts onion, two parts sage. Stir slowly over low heat. Do not scorch or the flavor will be bland. Drip the resulting oil over the stirge while basting with the aforementioned butter. Bake at 450 degrees for four hours.

When done, you will know because of the stirges crispy skin. Let the bird cool for 15 minutes before eating. Serve with yams and boozleberry.
Dertmuns Palate

My children, to you bequeathed the sun, but more importantly our sacred soil.

I, Baba, Grand Vizier of Abiz, Sultan of the western realms, patriarch of the wizened whealm, plutarch and gosmeer, pass this on to you, my children.

Be it known, that a royal carraige of the King will be sent, unsullied, to your doorway to carry you to the far reaches of the planes. The Tempolos, The Tremulos, and The Tumulos will be called on to protect you in your journeys. These demi-gods of the elements will guard you as you travel. The fire, earth and air shall be your ward.

Seek out the riddles to the fire in the sky, dig deep into its mysteries and return to our desert city with the answers to this riddle of the heavens. This is my task, given to me by our king, and passed to you, our young warriors of brave deeds.

Do not falter or lose faith. Our very lives and soil depend on your success.
A golden scroll

<this is written in a shakey hand by someone very old. It is in the writing style of Brosna nobility. Much has weathered and unreadable>

...No one will go. I write this after 15 of the heroes of Nordock are dead. All dead. We were the exceptional. One trip to these tombs left us bereft. I am a great warrior, and was but the porter. I was among the weakest, it was my fun slaying the legends, the great dragons alone, but I was merely the porter and left to carry baggage.     ...left all our heroes, dead. Do not go to the tomb. You will die. I write this in old age, many say I am striven by madness. All avoid me and my tale. I am old, but not insane.

For time immortal it has sought all knowledge. I am old now. And it has waited far beyond my great great great grandfathers, dervishers all, it has waited...

...though we planned for years, and the trials we practiced. Beyond all reckoning we planned. We felled all beasts, we felled all dragons. And one room took us all in a flas...

...and when the great mages welled their wills against us. We took them easily...

We entered the Tomb, and we fell. We fell as nothing takes and there was no return. I stood in horror as the heros fell. I was but laden with goods and supplies. Those companions before me stood and died. They died as newborns. Swiftly, and as easily as lambs. I ran, traps and undead on my heel...

...I write this in age, I am old. I write this from my tent. I die soon from the withering of time. Still no one in all the lands can defeat my blade, dervishers fall before me as chaff, dragons whine from the sight of my sword. Still I dream of that tomb. It is madness to me. Of its treasure and hiding riches...

I beseech all to avoid this horrer. The tomb remains inviolate, impregnable to the edge of time. Abiz is gone, a dust bowl of ill-fated claim, but the tomb remains. I die now, these are my last words written. My childrens children, do not seek madness, seek not this place.
Lost Home

We are stranded. Two ships, one for servitude, one for slaves. One for our leader, one to equip the other. We shall take this land, which they call Nordock.

This book is very very old, and contains two large fold out maps. Both are very crude, showing cities and a few highlights. One is of the mainland of Nordork, the other a rough outline of the underdark.

Map 1 shows:
Benzor: central. Brosna: east. Trondor: west. Tobaro: north. Abiz: small island off coast of Brosna. Northwest: Barbarians and Gnarled Fist. Northeast: unknown. 

Map 2 shows:
Underdark. Loknar: drow trade city, Chaulssin: drow capitol, Central: drow central, Mak'a'nor: Snirvneblin city, Gracklestugh: Duergar city. <marked boldly> Bharat: <there are markings here indicating this map was made by bharat hands> It shows a deep fissure leading down below the bharat mines.
Maps of Lands

Compiled by Dragot, son of Drycon.
<Sent by Priesthood of Benzor on a fact finding mission>

The Desert Blue dragon is an amazing creature, able to live for years on the moisture and moss of canyon walls. Rarely seen hunting outside of the sterile wastes, they subsist mostly on fish and the unwary that venture into their waterless territory. 

They have a deep resentment to most things however, and will attack on sight any seen intruding. The desert blues are all female, who guard the nests dug from the sands and stones. Their self-styed sultan, Lord Skree, resides deep in the sterile wastes, guarded by desert wisps.

Eggs from these beasts give a goodly sum on the open market, and have magical electrical power that courses through them. 

The desert blues fight amongst themselves for power, but always they multiply. It is well they do not hunt outside of the sterile wastes, for they are terrible foes.
Of Dragons

Mr. and Missus Bispot Bumbkey,

...then Bispot and I we went and we found it, and we takes it but it just looks like rye, and we filled our pockets and we ran.

Bispot he keeps it all, and he gets real sick, and we makes it back to Brosna, and he is real sick, and the priest cant do nothin.

So I heads back to the halfling woods, but Bisbot he dies on the way, and I writes this to tells you folks, cause I dont wants tah face ya, being Bisbots yer only son and all. But Im real sorry, and I buried him neat and proper.

Barnley

Many sheets of paper, scattered on the table, they are all the same, and look like a map.

This is a map of the entire island. Though it does not show great detail, it does show the major features.

The island is egg shaped, thinner near the north and slightly tilted to the northeast. The sea docks are far to the south, the road to the oasis of Hebdezi
curves around the southwest rim.

To the southeast is marked 'Dervishers.'

To the east and northeast is clearly marked 'Sterile Wastes.' A wall of rocks surrounds this empty region as if a wave of energy pushed them out. There are small pictures of blue dragons.

Far to the northeast are small pictures of ruined buildings, and in red letters, "Abiz.' The city is shorn and encircled by a deep crack in the earth. A small road is marked on the map from Hebdezi to Abiz, running up the western edge of the Sterile Wastes.

To the northwest of the road are small pictures of fire giants, spiders, whirlwinds, spouts of fire and piles of rock, but there is no writing.
Map of Abiz

Dear Randolfo, 

Not much has been happening as of last, we are still trying to get past the numerous undead in and around the city. The main gates are heavily guarded by ancient archers and swordsmen that rise from their graves to the towers. The archers were especially skilled in life. I think we are about to give up and return to the mainland, our food is growing short and as always the merchants here refuse to part with any.

Oh, just to mention it, we met a small ghost of a child wandering in the southern outskirts of the ruins of Abiz yesterday. It was at night and we almost passed him by. He paid us no mind but was heard crying by several of our group. We followed him for a while but he disappeared into the gloom. One of the elves of our group swore he heard the child mentioning a toy that had been stolen from him, a top. What ill fate this child met in life no one can say, but to meet such a fate, to be walking this place in that corporeal form for so long, his end must have invovled much evil.

Be well brother,
Baltrade of Blake

<Large tome filled with many stories of the short creatures overcoming tall obstacles. Here lies an exerpt>



...And so it's thus, Breegle, son of Boogle, kinshire leader of the stoutlads squadron, led his force to the center of the battle. The men and elves parted, as they knew the halflings would overcome any in their path, such is the fury of the stout unveiled. And so it was. Breegle whooped and hollered for the brave to press forward. Orcs, mangled and stunned, lost heart and gave way. But behind them the giants stood, resolute and grim, wielding sword and club, shaft and haft.

A silence overcame the fields of Kelahar, the dark elvin leaders of the evil foe stood quietly, their priestesses slowly droning incantations of woe and and hatred, the giants rocking back and forth to the malicious tune. Ashen faces of the humans began to face the rear, the good elves wide-eyed, frozen and afraid began to fall back. They understood the words of the followers of the dark queen, and were stricken by the ancient songs evil intent. All seemed lost. The forces of good wavered and began to peel away from the field of battle.

But in the center stood Breegle, surrounded by his posse of believers. A few gnomes also were there, and even one or two of the snirvneblin. Be it foolishness or bravery, they did not feel the wave of dispair that had grasped the army of good. Slowly at first, but with building might, they began to sing a song of green fields and flowers, wheat and honey, trees and small brooks. The evil shadow began to lift and new heart was felt by all.

The sun broke through the clouds, and the dark ones cowled and cursing began to disappear into the woods. And thus, the small folk won the day. The dark elves, in anger and frustration cried out that the battle was not over, but for this glorious day it was. The giants, seeing their leaders so shorn of courage, ran from the field. The humans rejoiced, the elves lamented the fallen, and Breegle quietly smiled.
Tall Tales for Short Folk.

This map depicts much of the known realms of mainland Nordock. Trondor lays far to the west, Benzor by the sea in the center, and Brosna to the east. Tobaro lies to the north.

Most of the map deals with sea lanes and trade routes. Roads are well marked out. The main road from Benzor ro Brosna is a bright red line. The small port of Mulrok is shown prominently.

Most of the main buildings are drawn in, detail is excellant in the cities. There is a vast space to the northwest that in bold letter says, 'Unknown New Territories'

There is reference to the underdark as well, 'drow' is written in small letters south of Brosna and 'duergar' near the village of Sholo. Both have small skull and crossbones near the names.

'Galdor' is penned in the center of Benzor, and a small drawing of a gold dragon stands proudly. In the corner of the map are gold letters, 'Gift from the gold, courtesy of the Golden Scales.'
Map of Nordock

This history has been compiled, written and sent to the peoples of Hebdezi in response to inquiry about our history and means. May trade foster between our peoples, as long as we maintain our presence upon your plane. The dwarves of Azer will forever be your allies.

<This book contains much dry information on all the known trees bushes and flowering plants on the mainland. It goes into fine description on the intricacies of tailoring dyes and how they can be manipulated into the powerful dyes that most tailors use everyday. It also goes into detail on fletching and bowyering woods.The book is not terribly old, most likely written in the last few years. For skilled crafters it holds no new information, but does provide a good read for those interested in such things.

Near the end of the book are some notes written in the hand of a person from Abiz.>


The Black Balsom palm only grows on the coast beyond the rim. It appears the spine from these trees are one of the hardest but most lightweight of any of the known trees, including all those written about in this book from the mainland. Egrol forged a set of axes from the wood and the earth demon hearts found around Hebdezi. Quite good throwing axes to be certain. So few trees grow on Abiz, that is was thought we should add these few lines to this book on one of our local, and unique species.
Flora of Nordock

<this is written in a fine ink by a skilled hand quite recently, most likely from an adventurer newly come from the mainland>


Construction of the Black Spine

For years those of Abiz have made and sold throwing axes of fine quality from the local stone hearts from elemental vents that encircle the town of Hebdezi and a rare wood found on the coast of the island. The process for this is simple if done by an artisan skilled in knowledge of these materials.

The stone hearts themselves are remarkable. They contain slight planar qualities. Elemental in nature, they slowly form 'pockets' of energy that are unleashed when disturbed by calling forth the small demons and mephits seen daily in the southern desert. The 'hearts' as they are called locally have a weight of planar stone, heavy but incredibly light.

When used in combination with the wood of the coastal balsom tree they make exceptional throwing axes, light but with the head of elemental stone, they strike with the force of a heavy hammer.

In cooperation with local craftsmen we have been doing studies on how improve on this process. We have infused the axes with the alien metal that lies about the sterile wastes, meeting with success. We have found many shards of the metal, and have bound them to the handle in such a way as to improve on the common breakage when thrown. Our experiments have shown that with the process now perfected, there is exceptional benefit when used against the elementals and golems that frequent the desert.

The crafters in this land are truely magnificient in their skills. Their knowledge of local manufacture is impressive. 

With respect and admiration to all those who seek knowledge for the common weal,

The Crafting Guilds of Mulrok. Mulrok Trading Hall.
